{{Infobox settlement |name = Ciudad Vieja |settlement_type = ''[[Barrio]]'' |image_skyline = PlazaIndependencia.jpg |imagesize = |image_caption = [[Plaza Independencia]] |image_map = Old Town, Montevideo.png |mapsize = |map_caption = Street map of Ciudad Vieja |image_map1 = Montevideo Ciudad Vieja.png |mapsize1 = |map_caption1 = Location of Ciudad Vieja in Montevideo |subdivision_type = [[List of sovereign states|Country]] |subdivision_name = {{flag|Uruguay}} |subdivision_type1 = [[Departments of Uruguay|Department]] |subdivision_name1 = [[Montevideo Department]] |subdivision_type2 = City |subdivision_name2 = [[Montevideo]] |established_date = |area_total_km2 = |population_as_of = |population_total = |population_density_km2 = |timezone = |coordinates = {{coord|34|54|24|S|56|12|30|W|region:UY-MO|display=inline,title}} |elevation_m = |website = }}
'''Ciudad Vieja''' ({{IPA-es|θjuˈðað ˈβjexa}}, ''Old City'') is the name of the oldest part of the [[city]] of [[Montevideo]], capital city of [[Uruguay]]. Nowadays, Ciudad Vieja is a ''[[barrio]]'' (neighbourhood or district) of this city. In the last couple of years it has gone through a major transformation that has made it the main nightlife centre in town. It is in this area where most of the [[nightclubs]] are, and also it hosts the 'Mercado del Puerto' a traditional venue for Uruguayan food and beverages. The main port of Uruguay (being the main Big Draft port in southern South America) is located in Ciudad Vieja.
Part of this transformation is due to the campaign made by the [[Municipal Intendent of Montevideo|mayor]] since this part of the city had been in a state of abandonment for decades.
== Early history ==
Until 1829 it was surrounded by a wall that protected it from possible invasions. After the wall was torn down, the only part of it that was kept was its [[Ciudadela, Montevideo|gateway]], which is up to this day an [[emblem]] of this part of town. Some streets remind the presence of the wall, like Ciudadela (''[[citadel]]'') or [[Brecha (street)|Brecha]] (''breach''), which has this name because it was near but at this point that the British managed to open a breach on the wall during the [[British invasions of the Río de la Plata#Second invasion - 1807|1807 British invasion]]. The old street Sarandí was turned into a pedestrian walkway in 1992, which increased its commercial and tourist attractiveness. In 2005 it was extended to beyond the [[Constitution Square (Montevideo)|Constitution Square]].
Ciudad Vieja has the most beautiful buildings from the colonial era and the first decades of independence. The [[Montevideo Cabildo|Cabildo]] (built between 1804 and 1812), the [[Solís Theatre]], the [[Montevideo Metropolitan Cathedral|Metropolitan Cathedral]] and several museums, like the [[Museo Torres García]]<ref>[http://www.torresgarcia.org.uy Torres Garcia Museum]</ref> are among the most impressive ones. Also several design shops and recycled loft floors flourish in the streets near the port.
== Places of worship == Several temples have been built in the historic heart of the city: * [[Montevideo Metropolitan Cathedral|Cathedral of the Immaculate Conception, St. Philip and St. James]] (head of the Roman Catholic Church in Uruguay) * [[Parroquia San Francisco de Asís, Montevideo|Parish Church of St. Francis of Assisi]] (Roman Catholic) * [[Nuestra Señora de Lourdes y San Vicente Pallotti, Montevideo|Church of Our Lady of Lourdes and St. Vincent Pallotti]] (Roman Catholic, [[Pallottines]]) * [[Capilla de la Caridad del Hospital Maciel, Montevideo|Charity Chapel, Maciel Hospital]] (Roman Catholic, Hospitaller Sisters of the Sacred Heart of Jesus) * [[Cathedral of The Most Holy Trinity, Montevideo|Cathedral of The Most Holy Trinity]], popularly known as the English Temple ([[Anglican]]) * [[Comunidad Israelita Sefaradí, Montevideo|Sephardic Jewish Community]] (Synagogue)<ref>[http://www.turismojudaico.com/contenidos/Uruguay/Montevideo/Para-Visitar/Templos Jewish Tourism in Uruguay - Temples]</ref>
== Government and infrastructure == {{expand section|date=January 2014}} The [[National Meat Institute]] (INAC), a government agency, has its headquarters here.<ref>"[http://www.inac.gub.uy/innovanet/theme/inac/foot.gif foot.gif]." [[National Meat Institute]]. Retrieved on April 18, 2012. "Rincón 545 - Montevideo, Uruguay"</ref>
